# riotbox-config-version: 4
# ~/.config/claude-riotbox/config — Persistent defaults for claude-riotbox.
#
# This file is sourced as shell script by the launcher. Values use the
# : "${VAR:=default}" pattern so that environment variables and task flags
# always take precedence over settings here.
#
# To activate a setting, uncomment the line. To revert to the default,
# comment it out or delete the line.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── Network isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Set to "none" to disable outbound network access inside the container.
# This prevents Claude from fetching packages or reaching external services,
# but also blocks exfiltration. Useful for auditing untrusted code.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_NETWORK:=none}"

# ── Overlay mode (podman only) ───────────────────────────────────────────
# When enabled, project directories are mounted via fuse-overlayfs so that
# changes stay inside the container until you explicitly accept them with
# claude-riotbox overlay-accept. Requires podman and /dev/fuse.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_OVERLAY:=1}"

# ── Nested containers (podman-in-podman) ─────────────────────────────────
# Passes --device /dev/fuse and --security-opt label=disable to the
# container, allowing Claude to run podman/docker inside the riotbox.
# WARNING: This disables SELinux confinement — the container has reduced
# isolation from the host.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_NESTED:=1}"

# ── Container image name ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Override if you maintain multiple riotbox images (e.g. per-project).
#
# : "${IMAGE_NAME:=claude-riotbox}"

# ── Agent selection ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Choose between Claude Code and opencode for `run`/`resume`/`shell`
# commands. Inside the container both binaries are always on PATH; this
# setting only affects which one the convenience verbs invoke. May also
# be overridden per-invocation with the --agent=<name> flag.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_AGENT:=claude}"

# ── Provider env var & routing passthrough ──────────────────────────────
# Whitespace-separated list of environment variables to pass into the
# container if they are set on the host. Used by Claude (provider routing)
# and opencode (provider keys). Unset variables are silently skipped.
#
# DEFAULT (when this variable is unset): the union of every registered
# agent's `agent_<name>_env_vars` declaration, deduplicated. Each agent
# manifest at agents/<name>/manifest.sh is the source of truth for the
# vars THAT agent reads — adding a new agent or a new provider key means
# editing one manifest, not this config and not passthrough-vars.sh.
# Today that union covers:
#   * Claude Code (agents/claude/manifest.sh): ANTHROPIC_API_KEY,
#     ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN, ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL, ANTHROPIC_VERTEX_*,
#     ANTHROPIC_BEDROCK_BASE_URL, CLAUDE_CODE_USE_VERTEX,
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_BEDROCK, VERTEX_LOCATION, CLOUD_ML_REGION,
#     AWS_REGION, AWS_PROFILE.
#   * opencode (agents/opencode/manifest.sh): ANTHROPIC_API_KEY,
#     OPENAI_API_KEY, OPENROUTER_API_KEY, GEMINI_API_KEY, GROQ_API_KEY,
#     MISTRAL_API_KEY, DEEPSEEK_API_KEY, XAI_API_KEY.
#
# Setting RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS here overrides the registry union with
# a curated whitespace-separated list of your choice.
#
# Excluded from the default by design — uncomment in your shell to opt in:
#   * AWS access keys (AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID, AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY,
#     AWS_SESSION_TOKEN) — long-lived static keys in an autonomous
#     container is a security regression. Prefer AWS_PROFILE +
#     AWS_SHARED_CREDENTIALS_FILE (handled by RIOTBOX_CREDFILE_VARS).
#   * SSH_AUTH_SOCK — Unix socket forwarding has a different mount
#     model and gives the container live signing access for the host
#     SSH agent's lifetime; out of scope here.
#
# Name-only (no `=value`) tells the container runtime to copy the value
# from the caller's environment, keeping secrets out of process argv.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS:=ANTHROPIC_API_KEY OPENAI_API_KEY}"
#
# Example: extend with additional providers (registry union plus extras)
# RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS="$RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS COHERE_API_KEY TOGETHER_API_KEY"

# ── Credential-file mounts ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Whitespace-separated list of "VAR_NAME:/container/path" entries. For
# each entry where the host env var is set AND points to an existing
# regular file, the file is bind-mounted READ-ONLY at the given
# container path, and the env var inside the container is rewritten to
# that path. Missing files or non-regular targets are skipped with a
# notice (no abort). Use this for cloud SDK credentials that live on
# disk and are referenced by env var.
#
# Defaults cover:
#   * GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS — Vertex / Google ADC
#   * AWS_SHARED_CREDENTIALS_FILE / AWS_CONFIG_FILE — Bedrock / boto3
#   * KUBECONFIG — kubectl
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_CREDFILE_VARS:=GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS:/run/secrets/gcp-creds.json AWS_SHARED_CREDENTIALS_FILE:/run/secrets/aws-credentials AWS_CONFIG_FILE:/run/secrets/aws-config KUBECONFIG:/run/secrets/kubeconfig}"

# ── Vertex ADC prompt ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# When CLAUDE_CODE_USE_VERTEX is set on the host but
# GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS is not, and
# ~/.config/gcloud/application_default_credentials.json exists, the launcher
# prompts (TTY only) before bind-mounting that file read-only into the
# container. Decline to manage the credential yourself instead — set
# GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS on the host to point at any credential
# file, or copy a credential file into a project mount. There is no
# config flag to suppress the prompt; the prompt only fires when its
# pre-conditions (Vertex on, GAC unset, ADC file present) are all met.
